    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-06-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="763"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d763">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2149.</note>
                <head>[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-06-29">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">June</hi> 29, 1911</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 69.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to advise you of a rumor which
                    has been brought to the attention of the Department, to the effect that the
                    recognition by your Government of the insurrectos at Tia Juana as Madero troops
                    would end the trouble on the peninsula.</p>
                <p>In this connection I have the honor to suggest that if political amnesty for the
                    participants in disturbances in Lower California will put an end to present
                    conditions, the taking of such steps would seem worth considering. Press
                    reports, however, indicate that Mosby and his men have surrendered.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.],</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
